# Power BI Assistant - Architecture Document

Version: April 2026  
Repository: `StoryTelling-powerbi`  
Scope: local-first Power BI assistant (Storytelling, DAX, Documentation)

## 1) Project overview

Power BI Assistant is a local web application for analyzing `.pbix` reports and helping users understand model structure faster.  
It combines a Next.js/React frontend, a Flask backend, an MCP tool server, and Ollama running locally.  
When a PBIX file is uploaded, the backend extracts semantic metadata through PBIXRay via MCP tools and stores it in frontend state.  
Storytelling and DAX use local LLM generation with streaming, while Documentation is rendered directly from extracted metadata without LLM generation.

### The 3 features in one line each

- **Storytelling**: creates a business narrative from PBIX model context using local Ollama.
- **DAX Generator**: turns a natural-language request into DAX using real tables/columns from the uploaded model.
- **Documentation**: displays technical report documentation from extracted metadata (deterministic flow, no AI needed).

### Global architecture (ASCII, 4 main components)

```text
Browser (user)
  | \
  |  \ HTTP (UI rendering)
  |   v
  |  Next.js/React Frontend (port 3000)
  |    - components/pages
  |    - React Context (PBIXContext)
  |
  | HTTP POST/GET
  |  - /api/pbix/upload
  |  - /api/story/generate (SSE back)
  |  - /api/dax/generate (SSE back, backend path)
  |  - /api/ollama/models
  v
Flask Backend (port 5052)
  - orchestrator
  - MCP client over stdio
  - SSE streaming to browser
  - NDJSON consumer from Ollama
  | \
  |  \ HTTP POST (stream=true) /api/chat
  |   v
  |  Ollama (port 11434)
  |  - local LLM inference
  |  - NDJSON stream chunks
  |
  | stdio + MCP protocol
  v
MCP Server (`pbixray_server.py`)
  - exposes PBIXRay tools
  - reads loaded PBIX model
  |
  v
PBIXRay (Python library)
```

### Protocol map

- Browser <-> Next: HTTP (page rendering + optional Next API route).
- Browser <-> Flask: HTTP POST/GET + SSE for streaming outputs.
- Flask <-> MCP server: stdio transport (MCP session).
- MCP server -> PBIXRay: in-process Python calls.
- Flask -> Ollama: HTTP streaming response (NDJSON-like line stream).

